            <phrase>
                <id>homeHead1</id>
                <sub>
                    <![CDATA[
                    What is Helium?
                    ]]>
                </sub>
            </phrase>
            <phrase>
                <id>homeText1</id>
                <sub>
                    <![CDATA[
                    Helium is a light-weight MVC framework, written in PHP, that is designed to be painless to install, simple to use, and highly extensible and scalable. It is built for a standard LAMP stack and comes coupled with installation scripts designed to handle the framework's package dependencies and configuration.
                    ]]>
                </sub>
            </phrase>
            <phrase>
                <id>homeHead2</id>
                <sub>
                    <![CDATA[
                    Who made this garbage?
                    ]]>
                </sub>
            </phrase>
            <phrase>
                <id>homeText2</id>
                <sub>
                    <![CDATA[
                    The author of this particular mass of code is an engineer named <a href="http://www.healeyconsult.com" target="_blank">Bryan Healey</a>.
                    ]]>
                </sub>
            </phrase>
            <phrase>
                <id>homeHead3</id>
                <sub>
                    <![CDATA[
                    Why make yet <em>another</em> framework?
                    ]]>
                </sub>
            </phrase>
            <phrase>
                <id>homeText3</id>
                <sub>
                    <![CDATA[
                    The genesis of this framework is rooted in utility. I wanted to have an easy to deploy and easy to develop development core that wasn't bloated with a litany of extras that I didn't want or need. So, instead of taking an existing framework and stripping it down, I decided to write a framework from the group up. This also allowed me to take care in how it is engineered, maintaining speed and efficiency as much as possible.
                    ]]>
                </sub>
            </phrase>
            <phrase>
                <id>homeHead4</id>
                <sub>
                    <![CDATA[
                    Who can us it?
                    ]]>
                </sub>
            </phrase>
            <phrase>
                <id>homeText4</id>
                <sub>
                    <![CDATA[
                    Anyone! Even those without extensive web engineering backgrounds can use it, so long as they have a modest understanding of PHP. Out of the box, it comes ready for deployment, and the basic method for creating new pages and services couldn't be simpler: Create a route, create a controller, and create a template file. Done.
                    ]]>
                </sub>
            </phrase>
            <phrase>
                <id>homeHead5</id>
                <sub>
                    <![CDATA[
                    What version am I looking at?
                    ]]>
                </sub>
            </phrase>
            <phrase>
                <id>homeText5</id>
                <sub>
                    <![CDATA[
                    This package is version <strong>{$setup[globalVersion]}</strong>
                    ]]>
                </sub>
            </phrase>
            <phrase>
                <id>contact</id>
                <sub>
                    <![CDATA[
                    For contact information, see: <a href="http://www.phphelium.com/contact" target="_blank">phphelium.com</a>
                    ]]>
                </sub>
            </phrase>
            <phrase>
                <id>pop</id>
                <sub>
                    <![CDATA[
                    Creating a dynamic popup is easy and painless with Helium!<br />
                    Simply call one of the following functions:<br />

                    <div style="padding:1em 0.3em 0.3em 2em;">1. popup.trigger('<em>[TITLE]</em>','<em>[URI]</em>');</div>
                    <div style="padding:0.3em 0.3em 1em 2em;">2. popup.raw('<em>[TITLE]</em>','<em>[TEXT]</em>');</div>

                    <div style="float:right; margin:0 0.5em 0.5em 0;">
                        <input type="button" value="Close" onclick="popup.hide();" />
                    </div>
                    
                    For more information, see: <a href="http://www.phphelium.com/docs/" target="_blank">phphelium.com</a>
                    ]]>
                </sub>
            </phrase>
